sections.text:
This study has been conducted for four reasons, both local and general. The first was to understand how basinal black shales of the CenomanianeTuronian (CeT) boundary event (CTBE), in the classical sections of Vergons and Pont d'Issole (Crumi ere, 1989;
D. Grosheny et al. / Cretaceous Research 72 (2017) 39e6540
Crumi ere et al., 1990; Tronchetti and Grosheny, 1991; Grosheny and Tronchetti, 1993; Grosheny and Malartre, 1997; Grosheny et al., 2006; Takashima et al., 2009; Jarvis et al., 2011) pass to the slope and outer platform facies. The second reason was to know how the CTBE crisis affecting planktic foraminifera (extinction of thalmaninellids and rotaliporids) is recorded in deep-water settings outside the black shale depositional area. The thirdwas to know if the forced regression associated with the CTBE on the western margin of the Subalpine Basin (Malartre and Ferry, 1993; Ferry, 1999) is also recorded on its southern margin, and therefore to see if the sequence stratigraphic context of the event is homogenous or not over short distances in the same basin, and on a larger scale from the published data. Finally, the coiling ratio of Muricohedbergella delrioensis has been studied in the basinal section of Pont d'Issole, and combined with isotope data to see whether the recent results obtained in the North-American Western Interior Basin (Desmares et al., 2016), regarding climate change around the CTBE, can be found in other basins. Pieced together, all the data now available lead to a reappraisal of the causes of the rotaliporids' extinction.
